Q1. What is PriorityQueue in Java?
What is PriorityQueue?
-->PriorityQueue is a class in the Java Collections Framework that implements the Queue interface. Unlike a normal queue, 
    it orders elements based on their priority rather than the order in which they are inserted.
    
    By default, elements are arranged in natural (ascending) order, but a custom order can be specified using a Comparator.
    
    Characteristics
    Stores elements according to priority.
    Allows duplicate elements.
    Does not allow null values.
    Does not maintain insertion order.
    Not synchronized.
    Internally implemented using a Binary Heap.
    
    Example:
    
    import java.util.*;
    
    public class Demo {
        public static void main(String[] args) {
    
            PriorityQueue<Integer> pq = new PriorityQueue<>();
    
            pq.offer(30);
            pq.offer(10);
            pq.offer(20);
    
            System.out.println(pq);
        }
    }



Q2. Which data structure is used internally by PriorityQueue?
-->PriorityQueue is internally implemented using a Binary Heap (Min-Heap).
    
    Working
    The smallest (highest-priority) element is always at the root.
    Insertion (offer) and deletion (poll) maintain the heap property.
    
    Internal Structure
    
            10
           /  \
         20    30
    Time Complexity
    offer() → O(log n)
    poll() → O(log n)
    peek() → O(1)


    Possible Output
    
    [10, 30, 20]





Q3. Does PriorityQueue maintain insertion order?
-->No.

PriorityQueue does not maintain insertion order.

Elements are arranged according to their priority (sorting order).

Example:

PriorityQueue<Integer> pq = new PriorityQueue<>();

pq.offer(50);
pq.offer(10);
pq.offer(30);

System.out.println(pq);

Possible Output

[10, 50, 30]

Although 50 was inserted first, 10 appears first because it has the highest priority (smallest value).





Q4. What is the default order used in PriorityQueue?

-->By default, PriorityQueue uses natural ordering (ascending order).
    
    For custom ordering, a Comparator can be provided.
    
    Example (Descending Order):
    
    PriorityQueue<Integer> pq =
    new PriorityQueue<>(Collections.reverseOrder());
    
    pq.offer(10);
    pq.offer(30);
    pq.offer(20);
    
    System.out.println(pq);
    
    Possible Output
    
    [30, 10, 20]









Q5. Does PriorityQueue allow null and duplicate elements?
-->Duplicate Elements
        
        Yes.
        
        PriorityQueue allows duplicate elements.
        
        PriorityQueue<Integer> pq = new PriorityQueue<>();
        
        pq.offer(10);
        pq.offer(10);
        
        System.out.println(pq);
        
        Output
        
        [10, 10]
        Null Values
        
        No.
        
        PriorityQueue does not allow null values.
        
        Adding null throws a NullPointerException.
        
        PriorityQueue<Integer> pq = new PriorityQueue<>();
        
        pq.offer(null);
        
        Output
        
        Exception in thread "main"
        java.lang.NullPointerException





Q6. How does PriorityQueue differ from Queue?
-->
| Feature            | Queue                     | PriorityQueue  |
| ------------------ | ------------------------- | -------------- |
| Order              | FIFO                      | Priority-based |
| Insertion Order    | Yes (generally)           | No             |
| Sorting            | No                        | Yes            |
| Duplicate Elements | Depends on implementation | Allowed        |
| Null Values        | Usually not allowed       | Not allowed    |


